commit 1cbdfb426394632f8a1619f0c3b76559d81f9101
Author: Oskar Gerlicz Kowalczuk <oskar@gerlicz.space>

liveupdate: harden FLB lifetime and teardown paths

This commit guards FLB counters and serializes access to copied incoming
FLB metadata. It also makes liveupdate_flb_get_incoming() hold the incoming
FLB lock until released by liveupdate_flb_put_incoming() to prevent
concurrent teardown issues.

> diff --git a/kernel/liveupdate/luo_flb.c b/kernel/liveupdate/luo_flb.c
> index cdd293408138..2cd5864c8b26 100644
> --- a/kernel/liveupdate/luo_flb.c
> +++ b/kernel/liveupdate/luo_flb.c

[ ... ]

> @@ -201,8 +208,12 @@ static void luo_flb_file_finish_one(struct liveupdate_flb *flb)
>  	struct luo_flb_private *private = luo_flb_get_private(flb);
>  	u64 count;
>  
> -	scoped_guard(mutex, &private->incoming.lock)
> +	scoped_guard(mutex, &private->incoming.lock) {
> +		if (WARN_ON_ONCE(!private->incoming.count))
> +			return;
> +
>  		count = --private->incoming.count;
> +	}

If a depending file finishes before the subsystem explicitly retrieves the
FLB via liveupdate_flb_get_incoming(), is private->incoming.count still 0
here?

Since private->incoming.count is lazily initialized in
luo_flb_retrieve_one(), won't this trigger the WARN_ON_ONCE and return
early? This would bypass the fallback logic just below this block:

	if (!count) {
		struct liveupdate_flb_op_args args = {0};

		if (!private->incoming.retrieved) {
			int err = luo_flb_retrieve_one(flb);

which seems intended to gracefully tear down unretrieved FLBs. Returning
early could leave unretrieved FLBs without their .finish() callbacks
executed, causing a resource leak.

Additionally, is it possible for a data race to occur when reading
private->incoming.retrieved in the snippet above? This flag is read outside
of the private->incoming.lock critical section.

If another thread concurrently calls liveupdate_flb_get_incoming(), it
executes luo_flb_retrieve_one() which sets private->incoming.retrieved = true
under the lock. Should this use READ_ONCE() and WRITE_ONCE() to prevent
compiler optimizations like load tearing?

[ ... ]

> @@ -508,17 +531,30 @@ int liveupdate_flb_get_incoming(struct liveupdate_flb *flb, void **objp)
>  	if (!liveupdate_enabled())
>  		return -EOPNOTSUPP;
>  
> -	if (!private->incoming.obj) {
> +	if (!READ_ONCE(private->incoming.obj)) {
>  		int err = luo_flb_retrieve_one(flb);
>  
>  		if (err)
>  			return err;
>  	}
>  
> -	guard(mutex)(&private->incoming.lock);
> +	mutex_lock(&private->incoming.lock);
> +	if (!private->incoming.obj)
> +		goto err_unlock;
>  	*objp = private->incoming.obj;
>  
>  	return 0;

This isn't a bug, but since liveupdate_flb_get_incoming() intentionally
acquires private->incoming.lock and returns with it held, should it be
annotated with __acquires(&private->incoming.lock)? This would prevent
sparse context imbalance warnings.

> +
> +err_unlock:
> +	mutex_unlock(&private->incoming.lock);
> +	return -ENODATA;
> +}
> +
> +void liveupdate_flb_put_incoming(struct liveupdate_flb *flb)
> +{
> +	struct luo_flb_private *private = luo_flb_get_private(flb);
> +
> +	mutex_unlock(&private->incoming.lock);
>  }

And similarly, should liveupdate_flb_put_incoming() have a
__releases(&private->incoming.lock) annotation?

